{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Sam Ash | birth_name = Samuel Howard Ash | background = solo_singer | image = File:Samuel Howard Ash in 1918.jpg | caption = Ash in 1918 | alias = | birth_date = {{birth date|1884|8|28}} |birth_place =[[Campbell County, Kentucky]], US | death_date = {{death date and age|1951|10|20|1884|8|28}} |death_place =[[Hollywood, California]], US | origin = | genre = [[Vaudeville]], [[musical theatre]], [[films]] | occupation = [[Singer]], [[actor]] | years_active = 1914–1951 | label = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Emerson Records|Emerson]], [[Okeh Records|OKeh]], [[Grey Gull Records|Grey Gull]], [[Gennett Records|Gennett]] | associated_acts = | website = }} '''Samuel Howard Ash''' (August 28, 1884 &ndash; October 20, 1951), usually credited as '''Sam Ash''', was an American [[vaudeville]] performer, singer, and movie actor who appeared in minor roles in over 200 films, including ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]''.
==Biography== He was born in [[Campbell County, Kentucky]],<ref name=allmusic>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/sam-ash-mn0000285833 Biography by Eugene Chadbourne at Allmusic.com]. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> of [[English people|English-born]] parents who had immigrated to the US. By 1900 he was living with his parents and siblings in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]],<ref>[http://interactive.ancestry.co.uk/7602/004117740_00618/40340669?backurl=http%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.co.uk%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3frank%3d1%26new%3d1%26MSAV%3d1%26msT%3d1%26gss%3dangs-g%26gsfn%3dSamuel%2bHoward%2b%26gsln%3dAsh%26msbdy%3d1884%26msbpn__ftp%3dKentucky%26cpxt%3d1%26catBucket%3drstp%26uidh%3djq5%26cp%3d12%26pcat%3dROOT_CATEGORY%26h%3d40340669%26db%3d1900usfedcen%26indiv%3d1&ssrc=&backlabel=ReturnRecord 1900 United States Federal Census for Samuel Ash]. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> and in 1910 lived in [[Chicago]].<ref>[http://search.ancestry.co.uk/cgi-bin/sse.dll?db=1910USCenIndex&h=4920593&indiv=try&o_vc=Record:OtherRecord&rhSource=7602 1910 United States Federal Census for Samuel H Ash]. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> He was unrelated to [[Sam Ash]], born Samuel Ashkynase (1897&ndash;1956), founder of the eponymous musical instrument store, despite some erroneous claims<ref name=redhot/> that they were one and the same person.
He first recorded as a [[tenor]] singer for [[Columbia Records]] in 1914,<ref name=dahr>[http://adp.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/talent/detail/917/Ash_Samuel_vocalist_tenor_vocal Discography of American Historical Recordings]. Retrieved 19 November 2015</ref> and the following year found success in a duet with [[Elida Morris]], "Hello Frisco!" from the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]] ''[[Ziegfeld Follies|Ziegfeld Follies of 1915]]''.<ref name="whitburn memories">{{cite book| last1 = Whitburn | first1 = Joel| title = Pop Memories 1890-1954: The History of American Popular Music| location = Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin| publisher = Record Research, Inc. | year= 1986| pages = 36| isbn = 0-89820-083-0}}</ref> In December 1915 he appeared on the Broadway stage, in a leading role in [[Rudolf Friml]]'s [[operetta]] ''[[Katinka (operetta)|Katinka]]'', which ran for over 200 performances.<ref name=movies>[http://www.movies.com/actors/sam-ash/sam-ash-biography/p234557 Biography by Hans J, Wollstein at Movies.com]. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> He recorded regularly for Columbia over the next few years.<ref name=dahr/> In 1915 he made one of his most commercially successful recordings, "America, I Love You",<ref name="whitburn memories"/> and in 1917 he recorded "Cleopatra Had a Jazz Band".<ref name=redhot>[http://www.redhotjazz.com/jazz1917.html Scott Alexander, ''The First Jazz Records'']. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> His regular appearances in Broadway revues included ''Doing Our Bit'' (1917), ''[[Monte Cristo Jr.]]'' (1919), and ''Oh, What A Girl!'' (1919) among others.<ref name=ibdb>[http://www.ibdb.com/person.php?id=66771 Sam Ash at Internet Broadway Database]. Retrieved 5 June 2013</ref> In the 1920s he continued to record for Columbia as well as for a number of other record labels, including [[Little Wonder Records|Little Wonder]], [[Gennett Records|Gennett]], [[Grey Gull Records|Grey Gull]], and [[Okeh Records|OKeh]].<ref name="allmusic"/><ref name="whitburn memories"/> He also continued to appear in Broadway musicals, including ''Some Party'' in 1922, ''[[The Passing Show|The Passing Show of 1922]]'', and ''Houseboat on the Styx'' in 1928.<ref name=ibdb/>
From 1929, he was based in [[Hollywood]]. He made his film debut that year, third on the bill as a suspect in the [[Craig Kennedy]] mystery ''Unmasked'', starring [[Robert Warwick]] in his first "[[talkie]]".<ref name=movies/> Over the next two decades he had hundreds of small parts in movies, playing characters such as waiters, news vendors, ship stewards, and reporters.<ref name=movies/> In ''[[Mad Love (1935 film)|Mad Love]]'', starring [[Peter Lorre]], his role was one of the detectives seeking the murderer. In ''It's a Wonderful Life'', in 1946, he played the part of the nervous bank teller trying to calm the crowd when they demand their savings.<ref name=allmusic/> Ash also featured in a number of popular [[film serial]]s such as ''[[Dick Tracy (serial)|Dick Tracy]]'', ''[[The Masked Marvel]]'', and ''[[Captain America (serial)|Captain America]]''.<ref name=allmusic/> He appeared in 205 movies between 1929 and 1953; his last two films were released posthumously.
He died in Hollywood in 1951, at the age of 67, and was buried at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Hollywood Hills)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]].
